<p><a name="Actions.2C_assumptions.2C_and_individual_preferences" id="Actions.2C_assumptions.2C_and_individual_preferences"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Rational_choice_theory&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Actions, assumptions, and individual preferences">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Actions, assumptions, and individual preferences</span></h2>
<p>The basic idea of rational choice theory is that patterns of behavior in societies reflect the choices made by individuals as they try to maximize their benefits and minimize their costs. In other words, people make decisions about how they should act by comparing the costs and benefits of different courses of action. As a result, patterns of behavior will develop within the society that result from those choices.</p>
<p>The idea of rational choice, where people compare the costs and benefits of certain actions, is easy to see in economic theory. Since people want to get the most useful products at the lowest price, they will judge the benefits of a certain object (for example, how useful is it or how attractive is it) compared to similar objects. Then they will compare prices (or costs). In general, people will choose the object that provides the greatest reward at the lowest cost.</p>
